European inflation slips on food
The acceleration of inflation in the euro area is mainly due to the rapid rise in food prices.
The price increase in November was higher than expected in the 13 eurozone countries, with an annual inflation rate of 3.1 percent after the 2.6 percent in October, the EU’s Luxembourg Statistical Office reported.
The official forecast was only 3%, according to Bloomberg.
Unlike the U.S., British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not cut the base rate, arguing that the reduction would lead to an inflationary spiral along with rising commodity prices and declining unemployment.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but close to, two percent.
According to an analyst, the ECB is trapped in the twenty-two: it needs to “talk” the inflation so that it doesn’t have to take action later on on this issue.
In Germany, inflation in November stood at 3.3 percent, a twelve-year record, while in Spain it rose to 4.1 percent from 3.6 percent.
Eurozone inflation has been driven by rising food and energy prices.
Wheat futures rose by 88 percent, and soybean prices have reached their highest levels since 1973.
Food oil and dairy products also had to pay significantly more in 2007.
World oil prices have risen 52 percent this year, and last month they cost nearly <0x24>100 a barrel of black gold.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1% this year to 2.5% in 2008, but will fall to 1.9% in 2009.
According to analysts, the level of 12-month inflation will remain at around 3% for the next three to four months, but the average annual rate will be 2.1%.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to cut interest rates twice in 2008.
Gallup sees a government crisis
After a long period of stagnation, Fidesz’s support grew significantly by the beginning of December, so it now has the largest camp since 2002, while Gallup has never seen such a low 13 percent socialist support.
In the case of the Commissioner’s party voters, the difference – due to the greater determination of the opposition voters – would mean more than two-thirds (71 percent) support compared to one-fifth (20 percent) support for MSZP.
