74 percent would say no to tuition fees, 79 percent would say no to visitation fees, and 84 percent would say no to hospital allowances.
If we look at the same percentages only among those promising their participation in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 percent of voters would reject the introduction of tuition fees, visitation fees and hospital daily allowances.
The most expensive is Auchan, Tesco raised by nearly a fifth
In the Budaörs trade triangle, hypermarkets maintained last year’s average price increase of 16 percent, except that VAT did not increase this year.
The Daily Economy article
On average, the Christmas basket of the Daily in the trade triangle of Budaörs increased by 16 percent again this year, but in each hypermarket there was a growth of well over a thousand forints in value.
Since prices in grocery stores had already "swept" in December last year, there was no drastic increase in the percentage compared to the previous high base.
But it is obviously frightening for consumers that what they were able to get under nine thousand forints last year is not available for ten thousand forints.
The Daily Basket exceeded the psychological limit of ten thousand forints by at least 91 forints in the hypermarkets examined.
The highest basket value was HUF 10,573.
(The price of the basket was HUF 6,800 in 2003.)
The prices of Unicum and live fish remained almost at the same level as last year, but turkey breast fillet, nuts and poppy seeds were also very expensive.
