In many places they save on disinfectants
This year, more than 1,000 infections have been reported in hospitals, mainly due to improper use of antibiotics.
The hygiene conditions in hospitals, the overcrowding of the beds and the overcrowding of the staff do not favour the cessation of infections, according to the head of department of the National Centre for Epidemiology.
They also save on disinfectants in many places.
Recently, MRSA infection was diagnosed in the traumatology department of the János Hospital.
A man who was admitted after a serious accident was found to have a bacteria that was resistant to antibiotics.
The patient is isolated.
A similar infection occurred at the beginning of the year.
The victim of a serious car accident was released from the hospital, but had to return shortly afterwards with an MRSA infection, and an important surgery had not been performed since then due to bacteria in his body.
Until 10 December this year, 1,094 hospital infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens were reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröcz, Head of Department at the National Center for Epidemiology.
This means that so many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have certainly been recorded in hospitals, the rest are unknown.
About two-thirds of infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, the methicillin-oxacillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
Staphylococcus aureus (SA) is a bacteria that one-third of people carry in their noses without causing disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g. pharyngitis, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infections) respond well to antibiotics and can be cured well.
However, when antibiotics are used excessively or inadequately, bacteria that respond well to antibiotics develop a highly resistant bacterium that spreads rapidly in inappropriate hospital conditions.
In particular, when the immune system is temporarily or permanently dysfunctioning, patients with a weakened body, elderly or low body weight may develop serious hospital infections such as wound infection or sepsis.
According to the medical director of the János Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infection, such infections are part of the daily practice of hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is just not there, said Tibor Nyulasi, where the presence of the pathogen is not tested.
Resistance to antibiotics
"We will isolate such patients, the nursing staff will take care of the patient in rubber gloves and masks, and we have the right antibiotics for their treatment," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Patients admitted to the hospital are tested for the presence of MRSA, but the infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling is not fashionable
The vast majority of hospital infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but the current hospital conditions and conditions in Hungary are not favourable for preventing the development and spread of multi-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection typically occurs in hospitals and old people’s homes, hospitals should monitor patients entering and isolate patients carrying MRSA immediately.
However, microbiological sampling is not in vogue in Hungarian hospitals.
The National Health Insurance Fund does not fund these tests.
Most cases will come to light if the patient has a detectable MRSA infection, the head of the epidemiological centre said.
The European Union has strict recommendations for the proper use of antibiotics in human medicine, and there are also domestic guidelines for the treatment of individual infections and pathologies.
Antibiotic therapy should be targeted, i.e. microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent the development of drug resistance, but this is not always observed in hospitals.
Microbiological sampling is even rarer in outpatient and primary care, said Karolina Böröcz.
They save on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most commonly transmitted from one patient to another by healthcare personnel.
Therefore, hand washing, the use of gloves and masks play a very important role, but there are also significant shortcomings in hospitals.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection or contact, but in domestic hospital conditions it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
In fact, the rooms are often crowded and the beds are often very close to each other, although epidemiologically, patients should be at least 1.5 metres apart.
Unfortunately, Karolina Böröcz noted that in hospitals with unfavourable financial conditions, disinfectants are saved, there are few nurses and many patients, so the chances of infection are even higher.
According to Karolina Böröcz, where appropriate precautions are taken, fewer such infections can be detected or the spread of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government Programme Against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA causes huge expenses for health insurers, which is why they are fighting it everywhere.
In England, for example, it included the prevention and reduction of MRSA in the government programme.
The programme appears to be successful, and the data reported show a decreasing trend in MRSA infections in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) prioritises the prevention of the development of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and hospital infections caused by such pathogens.
