Fodor and the six Hungarian percentage
According to Gábor Fodor, Minister of Environment and Water, the expert meetings will be completed on Tuesday, and on Wednesday, after the official opening, the negotiations of the international climate regime after 2012 will continue with the negotiations of the ministers.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world are discussing the Bali Roadmap, which sets out the efforts to follow the emission reduction period set by the Kyoto Protocol to 2012.
This issue is currently under discussion between developed and developing countries.
The U.S. has also indicated that it does not currently want to negotiate precise figures, although it is inclined to agree to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40% by 2020 compared to 1990 levels.
Another big issue of the conference is whether developed countries will undertake to reduce emissions and provide both financial and technological assistance to countries in need.
There is also an agreement on aid to developing countries.
The fund, which is provided for under the Kyoto Protocol, will be managed by a 16-member board, which is expected to be part of the United Nations Global Environment Facility (GEF).
Six percent of Hungary
Gábor Fodor, Minister of Environment and Water, on behalf of Hungary, supports the EU’s efforts to preserve its flagship role in global climate protection efforts and to facilitate the establishment of a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister explained that the EU is committed to a 20% reduction in greenhouse gas emissions by 2020 compared to 1990 levels, regardless of the success of concluding the "post-2012 agreement", and is ready to undertake a reduction of up to 30% if other large developed regions of the world and developing countries are willing to undertake commitments corresponding to their responsibilities and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that in 1997 the countries that joined the Kyoto Protocol set a target of a reduction of 5.2 per cent, including the EU-15 member states at the time - minus 8 per cent.
Hungary’s obligation is to reduce its greenhouse gas emissions by 6% compared to the period 1985-87, which Hungary will fulfil.
The stakes are high in Bali, as a long-term international agreement on climate policy must be reached within two years, otherwise its entry into force would surely be postponed to 2012. In this case, the Kyoto Protocol reduction commitments would not be immediately followed by another international emission reduction scheme, which the latest report of the IPCC, the UN’s Nobel Peace Prize laureate, international scientific body on climate change, points out.
This would delay emissions reductions and make it inevitable that the average global temperature rises above 2 degrees Celsius, with extremely serious and irreversible consequences, according to scientists.
