Political Capital: the Hungarian Guard raised the risk to the country
The activities of the Hungarian Guard, founded in August of this year with the support of the Jobbik Movement for Hungary, increased the political risk of Hungary and the region in several respects, according to the Political Capital Risk Analysis Division.
According to the company’s “risk warning”, the biggest political risk in connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard is that “with the escalation of the ethnic tensions already existing between the gypsies and non-gypsies in Hungary, even violent ethnic clashes can develop in the short term”.
The main reason for this is that the political strategy of the Hungarian Guard is probably aimed at provoking such an act, the research institute added.
“The public discussion of the Roma issue has been handed over to representatives of radical and extremist political groups, who have been able to build a political strategy on the gypsy-Hungarian conflict.”
This deepens the problem, makes normal dialogue impossible, strengthens extremists and increases the likelihood of violent conflicts.
In addition, according to the research institute, the activities of the Hungarian Guard under the influence of large domestic and international media attention “substantially undermined the image of Hungary abroad, especially in terms of belief in the stability and democratic development of the country”.
It is recalled that the reorganization of radical and far-right groups in Hungary, which have gained increasing publicity and momentum since the autumn of 2006, is part of the fact that since the summer of 2007 several organizations have been established in Hungary, calling themselves “national self-defense” associations.
“The common feature of these assemblies is that they define themselves as NGOs, while they openly proclaim the preparation of their members – whether armed or not – for defence (disaster protection, defence, law enforcement) tasks, in addition to the incompetence of the police, the army, that is, the state,” they added.
They noted that all this is done in accordance with the method which, based on the anti-political and anti-party nature of society, seeks to put various political aspirations into the civic garment.
The emphasis on civility and the form of association are therefore not only used to avoid the legal pitfalls of court registration in these associations, but also as a political strategy.
According to the analysis, the activity of the Hungarian Guard is also a risk-increasing factor from the point of view of neighbouring relations.
“In recent months, the Hungarian Guard has been referred to as a potential threat in several neighbouring states, and the ultra-nationalist political actors of some neighbouring countries are seeking to justify their own anti-Hungarian policies by referring to the formation of the Hungarian Guard.
All of this has an impact on the political stability of the region,” he added.
According to the research institute, the formation of the Hungarian Guard is not a unique phenomenon in Central and Eastern Europe, so political risks have increased for the region as a whole.
The operation of the Hungarian Guard is similar to that of the Bulgarian National Guard, the establishment of which was announced by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU) in August 2007.
