Witnesses in the eastern city of Lahore said about 2,000 lawyers protesting the state of emergency were injured by tear gas bombs used by law enforcement.
They threw stones at police officers, many of whom were injured.
At least 350 lawyers were hired.
Similar events took place in Karachi and Rawalpindi, where police attacked and wounded the lawyers.
Several people were produced.
In Islamabad, registered attorneys at the Supreme Court called for a general strike and announced protests over the arrest of some 500 opposition members, human rights defenders and lawyers over the weekend.
On Monday morning, the streets leading to the Supreme Court were closed to prevent the gathering.
There were several protests in Multan, in the central part of the country, and in Peshawar, in the northwest.
Since Monday, the lawyers’ movement has been backed by the vast alliance of religious parties, Muttahida Majlis-e-Amal, who “urged the people to send flowers to judges who disagree with the state of emergency and rubbish to those who took an oath before Musharraf.”
"Musarraf's promise is no longer valid."
The Supreme Court of Pakistan is directly affected by the exceptional measure announced on Saturday evening.
The Court will have to declare in the coming days the legitimacy of President Musharraf’s re-election by indirect vote on 6 October.
The President of the Court, Iftikhar Mohammed Chaudhry, was dismissed and replaced.
"Everything we're witnessing is illegal, unconstitutional and contrary to Supreme Court rulings," the president told The News.
President Pervez Musharraf’s promise to leave the army to serve as a civilian president has “lost its validity” after the state of emergency has been imposed, Deputy Information Minister Tariq Azeem said on Monday.
Musharraf had to leave the military uniform until November 15, the end of his first presidential term.
The Deputy Minister of Information also confirmed the news of the postponement of the January elections.
The Pakistani government has denied the country-wide rumours that Musharraf has been assigned a forced residence by his deputy general.
