Spectacular repair on the space station
Astronaut Scott Parazynski and the crew of the International Space Station (ISS) had to work more than seven hours in space to perform a spectacular repair of a broken solar panel that is essential for the scientific work of the station.
This dangerous space walk proved to be a record in many respects: the repair took a very long time, there was very little time to plan it, and it had to be done away from the residential modules with tools that were crafted by astronauts.
The problem emerged on Tuesday when astronauts separated the Harmony module from Discovery. It is a giant cylindrical element that will soon be the site of European and Japanese scientific laboratory activities (see box).
This module is a kind of gateway to laboratory modules.
However, we need to take care of their power supply.
The second task of the crew was to relocate one of the modules, which was already on the ISS, to its final location, producing electricity with the help of 17.5-ton solar panels.
The crew then began to open the module’s 76-meter-wide solar panels.
One of the harmonica-like foldable boards was then damaged by a cramped cable about 1 meter in length.
In order to avoid further injury, the board was not opened.
The mission of the astronauts was originally to take a walk from the Discovery space shuttle and then repair another solar panel with a faulty rotation system. Instead, they had to devote their entire time to repairing the damaged solar panel.
Scott Parazynski was chosen to perform the stunt by hanging from the space shuttle’s 30-meter robotic arm attached to the station’s crane.
He's one of NASA's best space walkers.
He is tall, strong, extremely skillful, has a muscular upper body and long arms.
The 46-year-old, doctor-educated man had to "operate" the "injured" solar panel.
After thoroughly assessing the damage caused, he cut off the faulty cable and fixed the damaged area with a few "rails".
He was also assisted by another "space walker" who stayed close to the safe passage, as well as other astronauts from the inside, including crew captain Peggy Whitson.
The tool he used, a mini hockey stick that was insulated against hundreds of volts of solar panels, was invented and crafted by the station's astronauts.
After completing the operation, Scott Parazynski waited for his companions to fully open the board, and only then packed his tools and returned to the station.
Yesterday afternoon, the astronauts took a half-day rest, and today seven of them returned to the Discovery space shuttle to begin their planned return home on Wednesday.
