The status quo remains
The elections on Sunday are not a big surprise: the vast majority of Russians will vote for Putin’s party, united Russia.
In this, the Russians’ demand for stability, a sort of arbitrary government, is manifested after a heavily manipulated campaign.
Today, three days before the parliamentary elections, Russian President Vladimir Putin speaks to the electorate via public service channels in a televised message, which has already been recorded, but its contents are still secret.
Putin leads the list of candidates for the Kremlin-supporting party, united Russia, which is expected to win an overwhelming victory in the elections.
At the reception of foreign ambassadors yesterday, the behaviour of the head of state did not reveal anything: it only made another outburst against the interventions of Western countries, which was a favorite topic during the campaign.
“We know the price of true democracy, so we want honest, absolutely transparent and open elections without any violations,” he said.
According to the opposition, this is far from the case.
The opposition condemns the campaign, which they believe has put pressure on the voters.
The leader of the Communist Party, Gennady Zhuganov, said: “There were no such dirty elections in Russia even in Yeltsin’s time.”
After defeating the protests last weekend, former world chess champion Garry Kasparov was sentenced to five days in jail for unauthorized protests and his lawyer claims he is still not allowed to visit.
“The Russians still think of us as ‘homo sovieticus’.
The predictable election results raise two more obvious questions:
Who will follow Putin in the chair?
Yesterday the date of the first round of the presidential election was announced in the official journal, which will be on 2 March 2008, and candidates will be able to indicate their intention to run until 23 December.
Since Vladimir Putin was elected in 2000 and 2004, his mandate cannot be renewed.
There are no other descendants in sight.
What role will Putin play in March?
Will he be Prime Minister?
Or will he, as the leader of the all-powerful Unified Russia party or the parliamentary majority, decide on the government and the president?
Whatever happens, the outgoing power wins both the parliamentary and presidential elections.
This has now become a tradition.
"The Russians are still thinking in the way of 'homo sovieticus': they don't feel they can control their destiny," sociologist Lev Gudkov, director of the independent Levada center, said in a statement.
Nikolai Koposov, historian of the University of St. Petersburg, goes even further: according to his theory, the country became Christian five hundred years later than Europe, so the development of civil society is also delayed.
Following the liberal reforms of the 1990s, “Putin went back to the paternalist model, which was perfectly suited to the people, all the more so because this new kind of paternalism was not accompanied by intimidation, but by a certain economic prosperity,” says Maria Lipman of the Carnegie Foundation.
Today, the Russians "willfully reject personal responsibility", which quickly became apparent after the dissolution of the Soviet Union.
"Why should we think?"
This phenomenon affects all sectors of society, including the business world.
The administrative elite is interested in maintaining the current status quo: the local lists of the united Russia are led by 65 governors, who come from the leaders of 85 Russian regions.
Freedom imported from the West often represents chaos, as was the case in the 1990s.
The public prefers stability.
In this spirit, the Russians do not vote for extremist parties either.
Tamara Cherednichenko, a 54-year-old teacher, concludes: “Why should we think?
The ones in power are not so bad, so why should we replace them?”
Depressing Memories
After more than 60 years of encryption, the Bad Arolsen archive has become public, documenting the fate of 17 and a half million victims of the Hitler regime.
The 47 million archived documents, which occupy 27 kilometres of shelf space in Bad Arolsen in Hessen, have so far been searched for "humanitarian" purposes, providing only individual and name-based access to the victims or their descendants.
In May 2006, eleven states, including Germany, France, Israel and the United States, agreed to open the archives to researchers and historians.
After all states have ratified the Convention, the archive was opened yesterday.
Confidential information
The opening of the archives in Bad Arolsen will allow historians to conduct research “on the relocation of prisoners, the residents of the camps and the health of forced laborers,” explains Reto Meistern, director of the archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross.
Until recently, several states, including Germany, have opposed the publication of the documents as they contain names and thus confidential information.
This may include, for example, the alleged homosexuality or mental disability of some deported victims.
The lists of concentration camps and the arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo began to be collected after the war for practical reasons, the purpose of which was to search for civilians deported or sentenced to forced labour and possibly provide evidence of their internment, on the basis of which they could receive compensation.
In Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees are currently working on the processing of tens of thousands of individual needs.
However, part of the scientific community does not consider the opening of the Bad Arolsen archives of outstanding importance.
"These documents are basically nothing new," said Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Center for Anti-Semitism Research at the Technical University of Berlin in 2006.
