Congress approves adoption of MiFID, which entered into force on 1 November
In parallel with the parliamentary process, which ended today with a vote in Congress to approve the amendments to the Senate, the government has initiated a social dialogue on the regulations on which the law is based, so that both can enter into force before the end of the year.
Representatives of the different groups unanimously highlighted the efforts of MEPs and Senators in negotiating and agreeing on the most favourable norms for investor protection, as well as the detailed regulation of the activities of companies, in order to ensure the efficient functioning of the market.
Mifid, which amends the Securities Markets Act, enables the modernisation of financial markets while strengthening investor protection, broadening the supervisory rights of the Spanish National Securities Markets Commission (CNMV) and promoting cooperation between the various supervisors in the European Union.
The new directive will allow for financial advisory services for specialised companies, but also for natural or legal persons, as well as for securities companies, securities agencies and portfolio management companies, to create a new form of financial services company (ESIS), namely financial advisory companies (AFI).
In addition, the law increases the number of systems capable of executing transactions involving funds, thus adding to regulated secondary markets multilateral trading platforms and internalization systems for executing orders, which compete with current stock market participants.
In addition, the Act obliges investment service providers to provide market information on the determining aspects of their business profile, their risk-taking and risk-management methods, and to keep records of all operations carried out in order to facilitate the control of CNMV.
The Congressional Economic Commission has introduced a number of amendments. Among them, it is of particular importance that securitised debts are treated as "complex" funds due to their high risk to the investor. This has been proven in the context of the US high-risk mortgage lending (subprime).
On the other hand, the transposition of the directive was also used to legally outline the scope of activities of those with economic and entrepreneurial qualifications, 30 years after the Royal Decree on professional functions that could be performed exclusively by economists came into force in 1977.
The Senate has proposed the creation of new players in the financial sector, such as an intermediary agent working for someone else’s account, who does not need CNMV’s permission, and can distribute products or acquire clients for several investor companies at the same time.
