What kind of insurance suits me?
Car insurance, which provides security for the owner of the car against various damages, involves significant expenses and depends on several factors, such as age, gender, date of obtaining the driving licence, marital status, type of car to be insured and nature of use.
Buying a car is just the first step.
In fact, choosing the right insurance is often more difficult than deciding which car you want.
First of all, we need to be clear about what this is about.
Car insurance is an agreement between the insurance company and the insured.
This agreement takes the form of an insurance contract, stating that the insurance company shall pay compensation for the fixed premium in the event of the event of damage.
The insurance premium is basically the amount paid for the insurance, which is determined taking into account various factors, such as age, gender, date of obtaining the driving licence, marital status, type of car to be insured, its use, and others.
Insurance companies determine the premium on the basis of statistics, i.e. a higher amount is paid by the person who presents a higher accident risk.
That’s why people over 25, or women, pay less, because statistics show they’re less at risk because they’re more cautious.
Similarly, insurance companies have concluded that married people cause fewer accidents than lonely people.
When it comes to the type of use of the car, the frequency is crucial.
More frequent use increases the chance of an accident.
When determining the premium, insurance companies take a number of factors into account.
Therefore, the owner should carefully look into it in order to choose the most appropriate form of insurance for his profile.
In the following, we present the most important factors for the choice, in order to best adapt to the needs of the insured and to establish an acceptable price.
When concluding an insurance contract, people under the age of 25 are faced with a number of disadvantages, such as lack of driving experience and the freshness of their driving licence.
Although it is most ideal to be insured against all dangers, there are also more economical solutions.
More cautious drivers will be able to take out full insurance with you, so they will be insured against all dangers and the price will be affordable.
In this type of contract, the insured will pay part of the damage.
"The amount of self-insurance paid by the insured depends on the premium; the higher the premium, the lower the self-insurance," says Luis Noguera, head of First Europa, an online insurance broker in Spain.
Another option is extended third-party liability insurance, where the customer insures himself against damage to others, but not against damage to his own car.
In addition, it will be insured against theft, fire damage and loss of the car.
A word of advice.
If you are under the age of 25, be careful and avoid accidents, as this will affect the bonus and reduce your future payouts.
Bonuses are defined as discounts in relation to the basic rate of the insurance company.
The penalty abolished in relation to the basic rate is called a malus.
"The amount of bonus and malus depends on the insurance company and its profits.
If the company has had a good year, it can afford to increase the amount of the bonus," Noguera explains.
Once the 25-year-old age limit has been exceeded, it is easier for owners to take out adequate insurance, as the risk of accidents is reduced due to the experience gained over the years.
We advise you to take out full insurance with you.
"In general, young people are not yet able to properly apply their experience in the event of an accident, even while driving," says the director of the European insurance company in Spain, adding that the majority of accidents occur in the second year of driving, when drivers have already overcome the fears of beginners.
If the insured is already married but has no children yet, it is best to take out a full insurance policy, of course, if your financial means allow it.
Insurance companies consider couples with children to be the least risky clients, and therefore the premium payable in their case is lower.
In this case, it is best to have full insurance with a self-supply (which can reach up to <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>300), or if you have a higher bonus, you can extend the insurance to damages caused to others from the third year of the vehicle.
"They drive more calmly, but at the same time they have more purchasing power and can afford to have a higher share," says Luis Noguera.
For pensioners, we recommend full insurance with a self-supply (about 150 euros), or it can be extended to liability insurance with a higher bonus.
Car insurance is a very important thing, not only because it protects the owner in the event of damages, but also because it involves a large amount of expense, so it is essential to choose the appropriate form of personalized insurance.
