Venus is Earth's Devil's Twin
Despite its harsh atmosphere, Venus is more similar to Earth than previously assumed: the European spacecraft "Venus Express" has detected lightning strikes in its atmosphere, and wind turbulences around its poles, such as those that occur on Earth in winter.
For nearly three decades, scientists have assumed that lightning is on Venus.
The European spacecraft "Venus Express" has provided evidence - electromagnetic waves have been detected on the periphery of the atmosphere: Lightning on Venus spreads from cloud to cloud at an altitude of about 56 kilometers, reports Christpher Russel of the University of California, Los Angeles, in the columns of the science magazine "Nature".
According to the famous "old soup theory", the formation of life on Earth was caused by lightning: According to the theory, thunderstorms triggered reactions in the ocean that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
Not so on Venus: "If life ever existed there, it must have been in the very early days," explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institute in Washington.
At present, there can hardly be any living organism on the surface of Venus: The atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, and temperatures sometimes reach 500 degrees.
"Venus may be Earth's hellish twin, but it is her twin," Russell said.
The main question of the Esa mission is why Venus, which is so similar to Earth in mass and size, is on a completely different evolutionary path.
The launch of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was a milestone in Venus exploration, because since the early 1990s no probe has been specifically on the way to find this planet.
The latest findings, presented in several Nature articles, suggest that Venus is more than unique in the solar system.
"They also point to the fact that the neighboring planet is more similar to Earth than we initially assumed," Esa said.
In addition to the already known Arctic whirlwind, the researchers have discovered a cloud vortex moving much faster in the South Pole.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of the Earth’s winter hemisphere, according to a team led by Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second innermost planet in the solar system has almost the same mass as Earth, and a diameter of 12,100 kilometers is almost the size of Earth.
The star, also known as the Morning Star, orbits the Sun in less than 225 days.
However, it rotates much more slowly around its own axis: a Venus day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although the surface temperature of Venus, coupled with a pressure of 92 bar, is barely reminiscent of Earth, scientists have assumed that both planets were formed under exactly the same conditions.
Both of them accumulated water, which remained on Earth as an ocean, while Venus left for the universe.
And while on Earth, carbon dioxide is bound in carbonate rocks, on Venus, it is a large part of the atmosphere.
